passages.text: 35-Page Survey Better Than Feared, But Agents Need to Address Al Cooerns

Our 20-partner survey saw 60% finish at/below plan + expert calls noted lower AF interest. For the stock to work post-print, investors need to see CRPO >10% + proof of Al monetization. CRM's EV/FCF is near 10-yr trough on Al disruption fears. While we view this as an overreaction, the ST multiple may be impaired by persistent Al headwinds until there's enough proof of Al monetization. We will host CRM's Co-Founder at our Al summit the week of 9/22, see inside.
**We will be hosting CRM's Co-Founder Parker Harris for our virtual Al Summit on September 22-**26,2025. Register here.

**Survey** **Indicates** **Stable** **Growth** **in** **2025** **vs** **2024;** **Al** **Still** **Ramping.** We surveyed 20 CRM partners to understand demand, macro, and Al traction. We note that this survey was more weighted to enterprise customers than prior rounds, making comparisons to prior surveys difficult. Key takes:
**·** **For** **2Q,40%** **of** **partners** **finished** **at** **plan,40%** **above** **plan,and** **20%** **below** **plan.**
**·** **50%** **expect** **stable** **growth** **in** **2025** **vs.** **2024,30%** **expect** **acceleration,and** **20%** **expect**
**·** **70%** **say** **that** **customers** **are** **pushing** **back** **on** **the** **6%** **price** **increase.**
**·** **Clean** **data** **is** **the** **#1** **hurdle** **to** **adoption** **of** **Agentforce,** **followed** **by** **decision** **fatigue** **and** **security.**

**Checks** **Say** **Decision** **Fatigue** **Taking** **Center** **Stage,** **Slip** **in** **Top** **of** **Funnel.** CRPO will face the second toughest comp of the yr on a reported basis before getting tougher in 3Q, while total rev will see the second easiest comp of the yr before easing in 3Q. Our partner convox indicated ongoing weakness in top of funnel activity as partners are growing below expectations for 2025, driven by lower deal volume/size/hours. Partners say decision fatigue is driving a cautious approach to Al spend due to volatility in the competitive landscape, pricing, and product functionality. Putting this together, we see little room for upside to cons ests. of 10%/8.7% for CRPO/total rev respectively.

1. Are Apps Dead? Apps continue to underperform infra names as investors fear that AI will displace front office names like CRM. Our checks this Q reiterated that disruption of the app space is easier in theory and highlighted the limits of vibe coding, while noting no reduction in seats. We believe investors will be focused on the # of paying/live Agentforce customers for early signs that AI monetization can offset potential headwinds to seats.

2. Signs of Core Reacel. Recall that last Q, Sales, Service, and Marketing and Commerce Cloud all decelerated sequentially \((\sim 60\%\) subs. rev). Investors continue to look for signs of when Sales and Service Cloud growth will meaningfully infect given several years of decel. CRM remains among the slowest growing large cap names in software while also lagging on OPM.

Our Thoughts on the Stock: CRM has an attractive margin expansion opportunity w/ OPM in low 30s vs. peers in the low 40s. CRM is down \(26\%\) YTD vs. the IGV up \(7\%\) and trades attractively at 16x '26E FCF, implying a \(\sim 45\%\) discount to peers at 28x. Maintain Buy.

We derive New Subscription ACV on an organic, constant- currency basis for salesforce.com, which we believe is the best indicator of future subscription revenue growth. We calculate that high- single- digit New Sub ACV growth can sustain HSD billings growth in the near to medium term, which provides support for our price target.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

About \(10\%\) revenue CAGR until Fiscal 2027. 100- 150 bps of annual non- GAAP operating margin expansion in F25 and F26. \(\) 375\(price target based on our base - case DCF scenario, which implies\) 8.1x EV/FY2027E Revenue.

- Meaningful revenue growth acceleration to near 18% long-term target, driven by strong new business growth, due to stronger-than-expected enterprise penetration, and/or pricing uplifts due to AI SKUs.- Annual non-GAAP operating margin expansion greater than 200 bps in F25 and F26, while maintaining 20+% top-line growth.- \(\) 450\(price target based on our bull case DCF scenario, which implies\) 9.8x EV/FY2027E Revenue.

- Top-line growth deceleration to high single digits, due to increased competitive pressures, market saturation in core market segments, or lack of adoption of newer products.- Non-GAAP operating margin near the low end of LT guidance, driven by reinvestment in top-line growth, pushing out cash flows.- \(\) 235\(price target based on our bear-case DCF scenario, which implies\) 5x EV/FY2027E Revenue.

Top Material Issue(s): 1) Data Security: CRM stores customers' most private and sensitive information; thus, the security of users' data is one of its highest priorities. We expect security to be an ongoing risk and expect Salesforce to continue responding to the changing security landscape and emerging threats. 2) Systemic Risk Mgmt: CRM serves its customers from third-party data center hosting facilities and cloud computing platform providers. Any disruption or damage to, or failure of its systems could result in disruptions to its services.
Company Target(s): 1) 40% Woman and non- binary representation in global workforce by FY27. 2) Conserve/Restore 100M trees by FY31. 3) 50% emissions reduction by FY31.

Qs to Mgmt: 1) Management has already met the 2024 goal of having 50% representation from Underrepresented Groups—will they continue their efforts to hire a more diverse workforce? 2) What actions is management taking to reach their emissions- reduction target of 50% by FY31? 3) Has tying ESG measures to executive (EVP+) compensation led to greater adoption of ESG initiatives?
- Accretive M&A and successful integration of recent acquisitions.- Higher traction for Data Cloud.- Cost-cutting to drive higher margins.- Earnings.

In addition to our partner survey, we recently hosted 3 calls with CRM experts for checks, including 2 large platinum partners (public calls; negative tone) and one advisor to multiple SMB/mid- market- focused practices (private call; positive). See here for speaker details. Key takeaways:

- Decision Fatigue Causing a Hesitation in Spend. Customers are overwhelmed by the rapidly evolving nature of the AI landscape, especially as it pertains to product functionality, the number of competitors, and pricing. Many customers are in wait and see mode and fear building a throwaway product, while other customers are opting to keep their existing systems and don't view incremental AI functionality as worth the hassle of adoption. As customers undergo a digestion period, they are increasingly cautious on spending for tools like AF, especially among enterprise customers.- Agentforce Interest Has Lost Some Steam. The first partner noted that 7% of his base is live on Agentforce, while the second partner noted that her practice has 50 agents deployed. Partners noted that the pace of innovation for Agentforce is solid for Service agents, but lack of control over ROI and confusion over pricing are still big hurdles for adoption. As a result, consumption and the number of live deals continue to lag expectations. On the other hand, the third advisor called out momentum within the retail industry for Agentforce, but noted that additional clarity is needed for pricing changes.

- Partners Growing Below Target for the Year. The first large partner called out a notable 22% decline in top-of-funnel activity as deal volume, size, and hours are all down in 2Q. For 2025, the partner was tracking 10% ahead of his goal for flat growth, but is now expecting growth to come in flat y/y. The second partner is expecting to grow closer to 8% for the year, which is below her target of 10% y/y, as weakness in CRM's Revenue Cloud Advanced offsets strength in Field Service. The third advisor noted strength in 2Q among SMB/mid-market customers but is uncertain how momentum will carry for the rest of the year. 2 experts noted strength in Life Sciences Cloud as CRM is winning deals despite intense competition from VEEV and IQV.

Proprietary Survey:
CRM Partners Expect Stable Growth
in 2025 vs. 2024; Agentforce
Momentum Still Ramping

Ahead of CRM's F2Q earnings, we surveyed 20 partners to understand demand, macro, and AI traction. We note that this survey was more weighted to enterprise customers than prior rounds and that the respondents differ from those in our prior surveys. We identify the results as Net Positive relative to past responses (16 responses), Net Negative (2 responses), or Net Neutral (8 responses). Our key takeaways:
- 20% of partners were below plan in 2Q, 40% were at plan, and 40% were above plan- Overall, 55% saw pipelines increase in 2Q
- Using a weighted average approach, partners expect to grow 9% in 2025

- 70% of partners say that their customer base is pushing back on the price increase for Sales, Service, and certain industry clouds that went into effect on August 1st- 75% of partners noted that they have a small subset of customers who have opted to renew early ahead of the price increases

- The % of customers who have purchased Agentforce/have live deployments ramped slightly from last quarter but remains in the single-digits- 45% say pricing for Agentforce remains confusing after the move to Flex pricing in May 2025

SUBSECTION 1
F2Q Business Momentum
20% of partners were below plan, 40% were at plan and 40% indicated they were above plan. (Net Neutral)
Over the past 3 months, how has your salesforce.com related business performed?

55% saw their pipelines improve while 20% saw their pipes decline. We are encouraged by the positive survey results, but note that our other partner checks this quarter indicated a slip in top of funnel driven by a slowdown in Agentforce momentum and lower deal size/volume. (Net Positive)
Has your Salesforce pipeline changed in May, June, July when compared to February, March, April and by how much?

15% saw their pipelines decrease as a result of the macro and \(30\%\) of the respondents saw an increase in their pipelines. Our apps checks this quarter indicated that tariffs had less of an impact than previously anticipated. (Net Positive)
What impact did the macroeconomy have on your Salesforce pipeline?
50% of partners expect to see stable growth in 2025, 30% expect an acceleration in growth, and 20% expect a deceleration in growth. (Net Positive)
What are your expectations for your Salesforce practice in 2025 versus 2024?

Using a weighted average approach, partners expect to grow 9%. We note that our other checks have indicated growing uncertainty for 2H25, with several partners growing under their targets for 2025, but we are encouraged by positive survey results. (Net Positive)
What are your growth expectations for your Salesforce practice in 2025?
70% of partners are seeing customers push back on the price increase that went into effect on August 1st, 2025. (Net Negative)

75% of partners noted that they have a small subset (Have you seen any customers renew early ahead of the price increase going into effect? If so, what % of your customers have opted for early renewal?
65% of respondents indicated that they believe Salesforce's competitive position in the market is strengthening, higher than 17% last quarter. (Net Positive)

Microsoft has consistently ranked as the number one competitor due to their presence in most of the markets that Salesforce competes in, although the % of partners selecting it has been steadily decreasing. We note that this could be attributed to the fact that ServiceNow was offered as a survey answer option starting in F1Q26. ServiceNow came in \(2^{\text{nd}}\) at \(25\%\) this quarter as the company continues to make inroads in the front office, further complemented by its strong presence in ITSM workflows. (Net Neutral)
Which salesforce.com competitor poses the single greatest threat?

SUBSECTION 2
Agentforce, Data Cloud,
and AI Adoption

20% indicated that customers were planning to adopt now vs none last quarter. \(45\%\) are planning to adopt in 3 months or more, in line with last quarter. Our other partner checks this quarter noted that innovation for Agentforce has been impressive and that deal volume is tracking above expectations, but that overall interest levels have been somewhat lower than usual as customers enter a digestion period due to an influx of AI tools in the market. (Net Positive)
What has the customer attitude been towards adopting Salesforce's Agentforce?

Positively, all of the partners we surveyed have customers who have purchased Agentforce, although adoption remains in the single- digit range (Net Positive). Similarly, \(90\%\) of partners have a single- digit \(\%\) of their customer base live on Agentforce. We believe that meaningful AI adoption will take time as customers experiment with AI, digest pricing changes from vendors like Salesforce and Atlassian, and keep up with the dynamic AI product functionality/competitive landscape. (Net Positive)
What percentage of your customers have bought Agentforce?
What percentage of your customers have live deployments of Agentforce for use cases like Sales or Service?

50% of partners say that pricing changes to Agentforce announced in May 2025 have improved flexibility and is causing more customers to evaluate Agentforce, while 45% believe that pricing remains confusing. Our partner checks continue to align with the latter. We note that many software companies are still evaluating the best method for AI pricing, including Atlassian and Salesforce, but we believe the right approach is one that enables customers to experiment with AI before fully committing to it. (Net Neutral)
What has the customer perception been to the pricing changes for Agentforce, including the Flex Credits and the Agentforce 1 licenses?

85% of partners believe that the customer's ACV will increase due to the pricing uplift from Agentforce, above 67% last quarter. Our conversations with customers have indicated a double- digit ACV uplift from Agentforce vs. core. (Net Positive)
How will customer's ACV with Salesforce change as a result of Agentforce?

Getting the data estate ready for Agentforce remains the biggest hurdle for widescale adoption, which aligns with similar surveys for Microsoft's Copilot and Atlassian's AI product Rovo. Security came in \(2^{\text{nd}}\) place, along with the decision fatigue associated with evaluating the many AI tools in the market. Our partner checks this quarter called out decision fatigue as a reason for growing caution around AI spend for tools like Agentforce. (Net Neutral)
What do you view as the largest hurdle to adoption of Agentforce? Please rank each category 1-6 (1=largest hurdle to adoption)

23% of partners see adoption of Data Cloud often, above \(13\%\) last quarter. \(60\%\) of partners have seen some adoption of Data Cloud, above \(29\%\) last quarter and ahead of prior quarters. Our checks on Data Cloud have been mixed over the last few quarters, with some partners highlighting competition in the data storage space and others noting an uptick in Data Cloud deals as more customers adopt Agentforce. However, most partners agree that Data Cloud helps unlock the full value of Agentforce, which could help drive increased adoption in the future. (Net positive)
Have you seen increased adoption of Genie (Data Cloud) by existing salesforce.com customers?

90% of partners expect ACV from Data Cloud to increase, up from \(63\%\) last quarter and above historical levels. Since Data Cloud helps unlock the full value of Agentforce, we believe that the ACV uplift will become more meaningful as adoption increases, but both products are still in early innings. (Net Positive)
How will customer's ACV with Salesforce change as a result of the Data Cloud?

Agentforce represents the most opportunity within the platform according to partners, followed by Sales Cloud and Data Cloud. Our partner checks continue to highlight the organic innovation behind Agentforce, and we see long- term potential for the product to help reaccelerate growth at Salesforce. (Net Neutral)
Please rank the top 5 from the list below in order of where you see the most sales opportunity in the next twelve months (1 being the most sales opportunity)

The majority (50%) of partners expect to generate more pipeline at Dreamforce 2025 vs. prior Dreamforce events. However, 40% expect no increase in pipeline generation, while 10% expect less. (Net Neutral)
How would you characterize your expectations for Dreamforce 2025 in terms of revenue/pipeline generation relative to prior Dreamforce events?

Keeping in mind that none of our surveyed partners rely on Salesforce as their sole source of income, \(60\%\) indicated that the overall business attributable to Salesforce is increasing vs \(8\%\) last quarter. (Net Positive)
Is the salesforce.com percentage of your business increasing or decreasing?

80% of partners indicated that they have increased the number of Salesforce professionals within their practice relative to a year ago. This aligns with our checks this quarter, which indicated that more partners are hiring. (Net Positive)

35% of partners noted that partners are happy and see an abundance of opportunity in the ecosystem, in line with last quarter, while the number of people who said the program used to be better and needs improvement dropped to \(45\%\) from \(83\%\) last quarter (note partners can choose multiple options). (Net Positive)
How would you characterize the mood of the overall salesforce.com partner ecosystem?

60% of respondents indicated that they believe Salesforce's promotional activity was typical, below 71% last quarter, while 35% said promotional activity was more aggressive than usual, slightly higher than 29% last quarter. (Net Neutral)
How would you characterize the company's sense of urgency and promotional activity into the end of July compared to the end of other July quarters?

30% of respondents indicated that the reliability or performance has gotten better vs. 17% last quarter while 65% of surveyed partners indicated that the reliability or performance of the Salesforce platform has remained about the same versus 75% last quarter. (Net Positive)
Has reliability or performance of the platform changed in recent months?

66Salesforce is betting big on AI Agents (Agentforce), but so are Microsoft (Copilot), Oracle (AI- infused CX), and Adobe (Firefly). The next 12- 18 months will determine who will be winning the battle.

66Salesforce has a good product line with innovation history. They are the best in CRM and they are trying to replicate it in another functions. I think that might dilute their focus. MuleSoft is good product that should be actively pushed to existing Salesforce clients.

66Overall, we see the growth outlook for our Salesforce practice solid but tempered by macroeconomic headwinds. Agentforce remains promising, but is still seen as early- stage in terms of revenue contribution to our services business.
66Salesforce professional services seems to be competing with partners for services business and hence partners are finding it hard to work with Salesforce as partner.

SUBSECTION 4
Survey Demographics
For which regions are you responsible?

About \(15\%\) worked with clients with 1,000- 4,999 employees (medium- sized businesses). The remaining \(85\%\) worked with clients with more than 5,000 employees (large enterprises). Additionally, \(75\%\) of respondents have been partners for \(5+\) years.
Which employee size range best identifies the majority of your clients?

salesforce.com, inc. provides enterprise cloud computing solutions to various businesses and industries worldwide. The company offers social and mobile cloud apps and platform services, including Sales Cloud for sales force automation, which enables companies to grow their sales pipelines, close deals, improve sales productivity, and gain business insights; Service Cloud that enables companies to connect with their customers and address their service and support needs; Marketing Cloud, which enables companies to bring in data from any source and deliver personalized interactions to any customer across any channel through email, mobile, social, Web, marketing automation, and data analytics from a single platform; and Salesforce1 Platform, a cloud platform for developing customer apps. It also provides professional services, including consulting, deployment, training, implementation, integration, and campaign services to its customers to facilitate the adoption of its social and mobile cloud solutions. salesforce.com, inc. was founded in 1999 and is headquartered in San Francisco, California.
Our \(\) 375\$ price target is based on a DCF (CoE \(11\%\) ; TGR \(5\%\) ) analysis. Key risks include significant deceleration in New Subscription ACV and margin compression.
